President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate David J. Glawe of Iowa as Under Secretary for Intelligence and Analysis at the Department of Homeland Security. Glawe is currently serving as the Assistant Commissioner at U.S. Customs and Border Protection, Office of Intelligence. He has over 24 years of national security and law enforcement experience. Glawe has previously served as the acting Under Secretary for Intelligence and Analysis at the Department, Deputy National Intelligence Manager for Threat Finance and Transnational Organized Crime at the Office of the Director of National Intelligence, a Counterterrorism Special Agent with the Federal Bureau of Investigation, and a Federal Agent with the United States Postal Inspection Service. He began his career as a police officer with the Houston Police Department. Glawe has received the National Intelligence Superior Service Medal for his contributions to the U.S. Intelligence Community and his meritorious actions to the betterment of national security. He holds a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Northern Iowa and is a graduate of the Senior Managers in Government program at Harvard University’s John F. Kennedy School of Government. President Trump also announced the designation of Rear Admiral Robert P. Hayes of Connecticut as Under Secretary for Intelligence and Analysis at the Department of Homeland Security. Hayes is a 29-year veteran of the U.S. Coast Guard and currently serves as the Coast Guard’s Assistant Commandant for Intelligence.